[2] Laos
Date: Wed 27 Oct 2010
From: Marc Grandadam <marc.grandadam@pasteur.fr> [edited]


Dengue serotypes in Lao PDR
---------------------------
Dengue infections have been reported for a long time in Laos.
Outbreaks occurred annually mainly during and shortly after the rainy
season. Previous reports summarized the situation in Lao PDR and
provided some indication of the number of reported cases and
mortality rate associated to dengue. However, there is a paucity of
data concerning the serotypes circulating annually in Lao.

Suspected dengue cases (patients residing in Vientiane with fever
more than 38 deg C or 100.4 deg F for more than 24 hours, without any
apparent source of infection, complaining of occasional headache,
myalgia and arthralgia), who visited the Medical Centre of the French
Embassy in Vientiane, had a blood sample taken for virological
diagnosis and investigations. Pending the completion of building
construction of the Institut Pasteur of Laos in Vientiane, a
diagnostic network has been established with the French National
Reference Centre for Arboviruses, Institut Pasteur, Paris.

Samples collected from 10 Sep 2010 to 10 Oct 2010 were sent weekly
and anonymously to France via rapid courier service. Serological and
RT-PCR results were returned by e-mail within 4 days after samples
consignment. Of the 30 samples investigated, 17 were found positive
for dengue viremia by real time RT-PCR. Molecular typing evidenced a
co-circulation of at least 2 serotypes; i.e., Dengue 1 (10/17) and
Dengue 2 (5/17). The last positive sample is suspected to be Dengue
3. Virus isolations are underway for a full characterization of the
viral strains.

Dengue 1 seemed to be predominant this year [2010] in Vientiane, but
the high proportion of dengue 2 and the possible circulation of a 3rd
serotype may sustain dengue circulation in Lao this year [2010].
Indeed, climatic conditions with prolonged precipitation are
compatible with a persistence of high vector densities in Laos. To
our knowledge no data concerning dengue serotype(s) circulating in
others Lao PDR provinces have been reported in 2010. Surveillance of
dengue serotype is requisite for a better understanding of dengue
epidemiology in Lao PDR, as well as to reinforce the management of
dengue in the country.

--
Dr Paul Brey, Director, Institut Pasteur of Laos, Vientiane, Lao PDR.
Dr Phengta Vongphrachanh, Director, National Center for Laboratory
and Epidemiology, Vientiane, Lao PDR.
Dr Jean-Marie Hospied, Director, Medical Centre of the French
Embassy, Vientiane, Lao PDR.
Dr Marc Grandadam, National Reference Centre for Arboviruses,
Institut Pasteur, Paris, France, <marc.grandadam@pasteur.fr>.

[PRO/MBDS would like to thank Dr Grandadam and his colleagues for the
information on dengue serotypes in Laos. For additional background
information on dengue infection in Laos, see PRO/MBDS posting Dengue
- Laos: RFI 20100826.3003.

In the WHO Regional Office for the Western Pacific (WHO/WPRO) report,
available at <http://www.wpro.who.int/health_topics/dengue/>, the
number of reported cases of dengue fever and dengue haemorrhagic
fever (DF/DHF) in Laos between 1 Jan 2010 and 16 Oct 2010 was 21 509
cases (45 deaths, case fatality rate 0.21 percent). Weekly number of
reported DF/DHF cases was declining after peaking in 8-14 Aug 2010;
7810 cases (provisional) were reported for the entire year in 2009.

The monitoring of epidemic trends of dengue virus infection by week
of 2010 (through 9 Oct 2010) by comparing to the mean and mean plus 2
standard deviations of 2005-2009, Laos is available at
<http://www.wpro.who.int/NR/rdonlyres/9877C9C1-3EEA-413E-8603-9B3C4893BD71/0/LAO.JPG>.

For a map of Laos with provinces, see
<http://lib.utexas.edu/maps/middle_east_and_asia/laos_pol_2003.jpg>.
The interactive HealthMap/ProMED-mail map with direct links to other
outbreaks in Laos and surrounding countries reported on ProMED-mail
and PRO/MBDS can be accessed at <http://healthmap.org/r/00cX>. - Mod.SCM]

