[3] Pakistan (Sindh)
Date: Fri 29 Oct 2010
Source: Daily Times [edited]
<http://www.dailytimes.com.pk/default.asp?page=2010%5C10%5C29%5Cstory_29-10-2010_pg7_10>


After affecting Sindh, the dengue virus has begun to rapidly spread
in Khyber Pakhtunkhwa [formerly the North-West Frontier Province],
while at least 27 people have died countrywide due to the epidemic, a
private TV channel reported on Thursday [28 Oct 2010]. According to
the [Pakistan] National Institute of Health (NIH), as many as 1170
people had been affected from the dengue virus in Punjab. About 93
more dengue affectees had been brought to various hospitals of Lahore
in the last 24 hours, raising the toll to 964 dengue patients in the
city. In Faisalabad, 8 people had been admitted in a separate ward of
the Allied Hospital, the channel reported. According to the Health
Department, the 1st round of the anti-dengue spray had been completed
in the rural and urban areas.

--
Communicated by:
HealthMap Alerts via ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>

[The 29 Oct 2010 issue of the Daily Times
(<http://www.dailytimes.com.pk/default.asp?page=2010\10\29\story_29-10-2010_pg11_8>)
reported that the (Pakistan) National Institute of Health (NIH)
confirmed on Thursday (28 Oct 2010) that so far 23 deaths have been
reported, 4 fewer than the report above. The NIH said in total 3100
patients suffering from dengue fever have been receiving treatment
from public and private hospitals in different cities in Pakistan.

On 17 Oct 2010 the Pakistan NIH reported 1141 confirmed dengue cases
(see ProMED-mail archive no. 20101018.3777), and since then has
increased to 3100 in 12 days.

Maps of Pakistan can be accessed at
<http://www.lib.utexas.edu/maps/middle_east_and_asia/pakistan_pol_2002.jpg>
and the HealthMap/ProMED-mail interactive map at
<http://healthmap.org/r/00tj>. - Mod.TY]

